<DOC><DOCNO> AP890615-0048 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0544EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels     06-15 0172</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels,0180</SECOND><HEAD>Army Reported to Kill 300 Uganda Rebels in Surprise Raid</HEAD><DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In a surprise attack on a rebel camp,government troops killed at least 300 insurgents and captured 500, anewspaper reported.   The reported assault would be one of the government's mostsuccessful blows against the 2-year-old insurgency of the UgandaPeople's Army.   The army attacked the camp near Sorito, about 220 miles northeastof Kampala, and battled about 1,500 defenders for almost two hoursSaturday, the Munno daily reported.   It gave no figures for army casualties in Wednesday's report. Anunspecified number of rebels escaped into the jungle, said thepaper, which is partly owned by the Roman Catholic Church.   Three rebel informers earlier Saturday told the army the locationof the camp, the paper said.   The Uganda People's Army is led by Peter Otai, a defense ministerunder former President Milton Obote.   He was overthrown in a 1985 coup, and his supporters have beenfighting an insurgency against the government of President YoweriMuseveni.</TEXT></DOC>